<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-09-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-09-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="928" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d928">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hill</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Eddy</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-09-28"><hi rend="italic">September 28,
                                    1902</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>(Mr. Hill states that Consul-General Dickinson has been instructed by
                            telegraph regarding his conduct of the matter of Miss Stone in its
                            Bulgarian aspects, and instructs that the legation equally do all in its
                            power and discretion with the Turkish Government to bring about Miss
                            Stone’s release.</p>
                        <p>Mr. Eddy is instructed, in case the agent should go to Sofia, to keep in
                            communication with him and with the mission treasurer, aiding the agent
                            in every possible discreet way.)</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>